The wonders of Western Australia

SPONSORED CONTENT

From the country’s sunniest capital city to outback adventures, swimming with whale sharks and meeting the world’s most cheerful marsupial – welcome to a state of amazement

Catching a glimpse of a humpback whale from a dramatic clifftop. Walking along vast, untouched stretches of beach as dolphins leap through the water not far from shore. Exploring the desert plains and rugged beauty of the outback as kangaroos graze in the distance. Western Australia, quite simply, is a dream destination.

Home to otherworldly landscapes, incredible scenery and unparalleled wildlife, as well as truly exceptional wine and food, Australia’s largest state offers nigh-on endless holiday opportunities. If adventure is what you’re after, then snorkelling off the shore of the Coral Coast, a Unesco world heritage site, is sure to excite, as is a visit to one of the 24 national parks surrounding the Margaret River region.

If cultural activities are more your style, Margaret River is also one of Australia’s most renowned wine regions, producing over a quarter of the country’s fine wines. You can work your way through more than 100 cellars, trying the local chardonnay or famed cabernet sauvignon and feasting at gourmet food spots along the journey. And the region is just two and a half hours south of Perth, Australia’s sunniest capital city.

Perth has been called the wildlife capital of the world – and it’s not hard to see why. With over 2,100 plant species, 15 amphibian species and 156 native birds, the city really is a biodiversity hotspot.

While the wildlife opportunities make Perth a must-visit, this stylish city has so much more to offer. After spotting quokkas (ever-smiling marsupials), kangaroos, whales and dolphins, head into the heart of the city, where you’ll get the perfect balance of excitement and relaxation. Lively beachside restaurants and rooftop bars allow you the chance to soak up the evening sun after a day of swimming and lounging by the sea, or to unwind after an action-packed wildlife tour. Meanwhile, the Swan River and the unique botanic garden in Kings Park provide a natural retreat from the buzzing inner city.

Getting to Australia is easier than ever and flight providers such as Malaysia Airlines will help you get there with ease and comfort. In fact, Malaysia Airlines’ London to Perth route is the best value of its Australian offerings, with return flight options from as low as £894 (I’m seeing lower prices) return. Flight time is under 20 hours, with one stop in Kuala Lumpur.

A road trip that will take you through this stunning part of the state. You start off in Perth, then head for the captivating landscapes of Margaret River and Albany before returning for a four-night stay at the QT Perth hotel.

11 nights from £5,735pp (inc flights)

You start this adventure by exploring Perth’s highlights from a stay in the Como The Treasury hotel, in the heart of the city.
